The paper proposes a method for generating vector representations of biological entities in ontologies by combining formal ontology axioms and annotation axioms from the ontology meta-data. The method uses a Word2Vec model that has been pre-trained on PubMed abstracts to produce feature vectors from the collected data. The paper also validates the method by using the obtained vector representations to predict protein-protein interaction and gene-disease associations. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the following arXiv CS sub-categories: 
- cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) because the paper proposes a method that uses machine learning techniques to generate vector representations of biological entities. 
- cs.LG (Machine Learning) because the paper uses a Word2Vec model to produce feature vectors from the collected data. 
- cs.CL (Computation and Language) because the paper deals with natural language processing techniques to generate vector representations of biomedical entities. 
- cs.DB (Databases) because the paper deals with ontologies that are widely used for data annotation, integration, and analysis. 
- cs.IR (Information Retrieval) because the paper evaluates the method by using the obtained vector representations to predict protein-protein interaction and gene-disease associations, which are tasks related to information retrieval.
